### Smart Pointers

Smart pointers are RAII wrappers around raw pointers that automatically manage memory. They ensure proper deallocation and prevent memory leaks.

---

### Types of Smart Pointers

| Smart Pointer | Header | Ownership |
|---------------|--------|-----------|
| `std::unique_ptr` | `<memory>` | Exclusive ownership |
| `std::shared_ptr` | `<memory>` | Shared ownership (reference counted) |
| `std::weak_ptr` | `<memory>` | Non-owning observer |

---

### unique_ptr

```cpp
#include <memory>

// Preferred creation (C++14)
auto ptr = make_unique<int>(42);

// Cannot be copied, only moved
auto ptr2 = std::move(ptr);  // Transfer ownership
// ptr is now nullptr
```

---

### shared_ptr

```cpp
auto sptr = make_shared<MyClass>();

{
  auto sptr2 = sptr;  // Reference count: 2
  // Both pointers share ownership
}
// Reference count back to 1
// Object deleted when ref count reaches 0
```

---

### weak_ptr

```cpp
auto sptr = make_shared<int>(42);
weak_ptr<int> wptr = sptr;  // Non-owning reference

if (auto locked = wptr.lock()) {  // Try to acquire shared ownership
  cout << *locked;
} else {
  cout << "Object already deleted";
}
```

---

### Raw vs Smart Pointers

| Aspect | Raw Pointer | Smart Pointer |
|--------|-------------|---------------|
| Memory management | Manual | Automatic |
| Exception safety | Risk of leaks | Safe |
| Nullable | Yes | Yes |
| Ownership semantics | Unclear | Explicit |
| Performance | No overhead | Slight overhead (shared_ptr) |

---

> **Key Point:** Prefer `std::unique_ptr` by default. Use `std::shared_ptr` only when shared ownership is required. Avoid raw `new`/`delete` in modern C++. Always use `std::make_unique` and `std::make_shared`.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

class Resource {
public:
  Resource() { cout << "Resource acquired" << endl; }
  ~Resource() { cout << "Resource released" << endl; }
  void work() { cout << "Working..." << endl; }
};

int main() {
  unique_ptr<Resource> ptr = make_unique<Resource>();
  ptr->work();
  // Automatically deleted when ptr goes out of scope
  return 0;
}
